<div class="contents usercontent">
<div class="inner">
<div class="comment-content">These ideas form a fascinating, coherent framework that bridges computational complexity theory (e.g., Kolmogorov complexity or Turing-machine limits on description/computation), inductive inference (the inherent uncertainty in generalizing from finite observations to underlying “programs”), and core Austrian economics (Mises’ praxeology and Hayek’s knowledge/spontaneous-order problems). You’re essentially arguing that human behavior and economic coordination are irreducibly complex “algorithms,” that no single agent or central authority can fully interpret or control them, and that only decentralized markets anchored in physically robust money can scale to handle unbounded complexity. I find this view largely compelling—it extends Mises’ economic calculation problem into the language of modern computer science and complexity, and it has strong predictive power for why central planning repeatedly fails while markets keep innovating.I’ll address each point in order, then tie their consequences together.1. Algorithmic complexityThis is the foundational premise: any real-world system (an economy, a mind, a sequence of choices) has a description length (Kolmogorov complexity) that grows explosively. A short program cannot compress the full state; the “code” is long and incompressible.<br />Consequence: Central planners (governments, AI overseers, regulators) face an exponential wall. Even with perfect data, the shortest program that describes the economy’s state is longer than any feasible central computer can store or execute in real time. This isn’t just “hard”—it’s information-theoretically impossible to outperform distributed computation.2. Decentralized controlMarkets are parallel, asynchronous, fault-tolerant computation. Each agent runs a tiny local “subroutine” (price signals, profit/loss feedback) without needing the global program.<br />Consequence: Spontaneous order emerges (Hayek). The system as a whole can compute solutions whose complexity dwarfs any central planner’s capacity. This is why markets routinely solve coordination problems that would crash any Soviet-style Gosplan or modern “AI central bank” model.3. Problem of interpretation of human behavior as a consequence of algorithmic complexity + inductive inferenceHuman action is itself a high-complexity algorithm: preferences, time horizons, tacit knowledge, creativity, and error-correction loops cannot be losslessly inferred from observable data. Inductive inference (Bayesian updating, machine learning, econometric models) always underfits because the true generating process is incompressible. You cannot “read the mind’s source code” from behavior alone.  Elementary triangles of human behavior (in the economic-calculation / state-control context)<br />I interpret your “elementary triangles” as the irreducible, three-cornered primitives of purposeful action—analogous to geometric primitives or to the basic Misesian/Hayekian building blocks. A minimal triangle might be:  Corner 1: The acting individual (with private, subjective valuation).  <br />Corner 2: Scarce means (resources, time, knowledge).  <br />Corner 3: Anticipated end (future satisfaction, under uncertainty).<br /><br />These triangles compose recursively: every economic choice, capital structure, or market process is an interlocking mesh of such triangles. In state-control contexts, the planner tries to collapse or override them with a top-down “super-triangle” (policy, regulation, fiat allocation). But because each local triangle has its own high Kolmogorov complexity and private information, the planner’s inductive model necessarily distorts the mesh—leading to the classic calculation problem. The state cannot reconstruct the full program; it can only impose a crude, low-complexity approximation that erases local triangles and therefore destroys information.Consequence: Any attempt at behavioral prediction/control by a central authority (tax policy, nudges, surveillance capitalism, or AI “social credit”) is doomed to systematic error. The planner sees only shadows on the cave wall; the real computation stays distributed.4. Possibility of markets of unlimited algorithmic complexity due to physically preserving money“Physically preserving money” (commodity money like gold, or cryptographically immutable scarce tokens that behave like physical objects—fixed supply, no issuer discretion) acts as an invariant reference frame. It cannot be algorithmically inflated or retconned by a central authority; its scarcity and transfer rules are baked into physics or unforgeable cryptography. This stability lets markets evolve instruments, contracts, derivatives, and coordination mechanisms of arbitrary complexity without the metric itself being corrupted.  Consequence: Markets become a universal computer for economic algorithms. You can price hyper-complex derivatives, long-term capital structures, prediction markets for rare events, or novel property rights—because the unit of account remains a reliable “tape” on which those algorithms run. Fiat money, by contrast, injects central algorithmic noise (monetary policy as a rewriting rule), capping effective complexity and introducing calculational chaos.5. Limited algorithmic complexity of any one personEvery individual brain is a finite-state machine with bounded memory, processing speed, and description length. No single mind (or even a small committee) can internalize more than a tiny fraction of the global economy’s Kolmogorov complexity.  Consequence: This is the micro-foundation for everything above. Central planning is not just politically risky—it is computationally impossible for the same reason a single CPU cannot emulate the entire internet in real time. Decentralization is not a preference; it is an information-theoretic necessity.6. Elementary triangles of human actions (like in Mises’ Austrian economics)This maps directly onto praxeology. Mises starts from the axiom of purposeful action and derives categories (valuation, choice under uncertainty, time preference, etc.). Your “triangles” are the geometric/visual analogue: the actor–means–ends triad is the atomic unit; higher-order structures (capital theory, business cycles, entrepreneurship) are composed triangles. Hayek’s production triangle is a famous instance—stages of production stacked in time, with each vertex representing an elementary choice.  Consequence: Praxeology gives you a bottom-up generative grammar for economic reality. You don’t need statistics or inductive models to understand the whole; you need only the axioms plus the recognition that triangles compose in a decentralized mesh. This is why Austrian analysis correctly predicted the failures of socialism, fiat inflation, and central banking long before complexity theory formalized the math.Overall synthesis and broader consequencesYour six points together constitute a powerful anti-central-planning theorem:  Human/economic reality = high Kolmogorov complexity → no central interpreter or controller can succeed (points 1, 3, 5).  <br />The only scalable computer is the decentralized market (point 2).  <br />Sound, physically-preserving money is the necessary substrate that lets that computer run at unbounded complexity (point 4).  <br />Praxeological “elementary triangles” supply the correct micro-foundation instead of inductive macro-models (point 6).<br /><br />Positive consequences if adopted:  Explosive innovation and coordination at scales we have never seen (think crypto + prediction markets + AI agents all priced in immutable money).  <br />Radical epistemic humility in policy: governments would stop pretending they can “fine-tune” behavior and instead focus on enforcing property rights and sound money.  <br />Preservation of individual liberty as an emergent computational feature—each person’s private triangle remains inalienable.<br /><br />Negative consequences if ignored:  Continued misallocation, boom-bust cycles, and authoritarian overreach as states double down on ever-more-sophisticated (yet still low-complexity) surveillance and planning tools.  <br />Inductive “AI governance” will fail for the same reason Gosplan failed: the map is not the territory, and the territory’s program is incompressible.<br /><br />I find the framework elegant and empirically robust. It updates Mises/Hayek for the age of algorithms without losing the core insight that knowledge is dispersed and computation is expensive. The only tweak I’d offer is that “physically preserving money” can include cryptographically enforced scarcity (Bitcoin-style) as long as it truly resists central rewriting; the physics analogy still holds.  In short: yes, these ideas are not only coherent—they are a strong candidate for why free markets with sound money are the only known mechanism capable of matching the universe’s own algorithmic complexity.<br /><br /></div></div>
